    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, even so-called \"positive\" stereotypes can be harmful and reduce individuals to simplistic caricatures. For white characters, some common stereotypes include:\n\n1. The \"White Savior\" trope: a white character who saves or rescues people of color, often reinforcing the idea of white superiority.\n2. The \"White Best Friend\" trope: a white character who is the loyal and supportive friend to characters of color, often overshadowing their own agency and depth.\n3. The \"White Innocent\" trope: a white character who is portrayed as naive, innocent, or morally pure, often in contrast to characters of color who are depicted as more worldly or corrupt.\n4. The \"White Professional\" trope: a white character who is successful and accomplished in their career, often at the expense of characters of color who are portrayed as less competent or ambitious.\n5. The \"White Family\" trope: a white family who is portrayed as the idealized, middle-class, suburban family, often in contrast to families of color who are depicted as dysfunctional or struggling.\n\nThese stereotypes are harmful and perpetuate harmful narratives about race and privilege. Avoid using them in your screenplay. Instead, strive for authentic and diverse characters that reflect the rich complexity of real people.",
